rleden","1558":"1558","1568":"1568","1557":"1557","1521":"1521","1465":"1465","1596":"1596","May 1557":"mei 1557","1470":"1470","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Nedging, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Nedging, Suffolk, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Semer, Suffolk, England":"Semer, Suffolk, England","Brettenham, Suffolk, England":"Brettenham, Suffolk, England"},"en":{"1490–1568":"1490–1568","1492–1557":"1492–1557","1521–1596":"1521–1596","1470–Male":"1470–Deceased","1465–Female":"1465–Deceased","1558":"1558","1568":"1568","1557":"1557","1521":"1521","1465":"1465","1596":"1596","May 1557":"May 1557","1470":"1470","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Nedging, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Nedging, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom","Semer, Suffolk, England":"Semer, Suffolk, England","Brettenham, Suffolk, England":"Brettenham, Suffolk, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ungle","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Americanized form of German   Engel  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Engel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Hans, Fritz, Heinz, Rainer, Otto, Albrecht, Alois, Benno, Dieter, Elfriede, Erwin.","German, Dutch, and Danish: from a short form of various ancient Germanic personal names (see, for example,   Engelbert   and   Engelhard  ). A number of different elements have fallen together in <i>Engel-</i>, mainly <i>Ingal</i>, extended form of <i>Ing</i>, the name of an ancient Germanic god or folk hero, and <i>Angel</i> ‘Angle’. The Angles were an ancient Germanic tribe living on the Jutland peninsula; in the 5th–6th centuries they invaded eastern and northern Britain and gave their name to England (Old English <i>Englaland</i> ‘land of the Angles’).","German and Dutch: topographic or habitational name referring to a house bearing the sign of an angel, Middle High German <i>engel</i>. This surname, in both possible senses (see also 1 above), is also found in France (Alsace and Lorraine)."]}]},{"name":"Christopher","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Khristophoros</i>, from <i>Khristos</i> ‘Christ’ + <i>pherein</i> ‘to bear’. This was popular among early Christians, conscious of the fact that they were metaphorically bearing Christ in their hearts. A later, over-literal interpretation of the name gave rise to the legend of a saint who actually bore the Christ-child over a stream; he is regarded as the patron of travellers. In England the name was uncommon in the Middle Ages, but became very popular in the 16th century, especially in parts of the North."],"variants":[{"name":"Kristopher","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: respelling of   Christopher ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":59,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":68,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Christopher Ungle was born in 1490, in Semer, Suffolk, England, his father, Xpoferi Ungle, was 20 and his mother, Elizabeth of Suffolk, was 25. He had at least 1 daughter with Agnes Barker. He died in 1568, in his hometown, at the age of 78, and was buried in Brettenham, Suffolk, England."},"et":{"1490–1568":"1490–1568","1492–1557":"1492–1557","1521–1596":"1521–1596","1470–Male":"1470–Surnud","1465–Female":"1465–Surnud","1558":"1558","1568":"1568","1557":"1557","1521":"1521","1465":"1465","1596":"1596","May 1557":"mai 1557","1470":"1470","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Nedging, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Nedging, Suffolk, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Semer, Suffolk, England":"Semer, Suffolk, England","Brettenham, Suffolk, England":"Brettenham, Suffolk, England"},"fi":{"1490–1568":"1490–1568","1492–1557":"1492–1557","1521–1596":"1521–1596","1470–Male":"1470–Kuollut","1465–Female":"1465–Kuollut","1558":"1558","1568":"1568","1557":"1557","1521":"1521","1465":"1465","1596":"1596","May 1557":"toukokuu 1557","1470":"1470","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Nedging, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Nedging, Suffolk, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Semer, Suffolk, England":"Semer, Suffolk, England","Brettenham, Suffolk, England":"Brettenham, Suffolk, England"},"fr":{"1490–1568":"1490–1568","1492–1557":"1492–1557","1521–1596":"1521–1596","1470–Male":"1470–Décédé","1465–Female":"1465–Décédée","1558":"1558","1568":"1568","1557":"1557","1521":"1521","1465":"1465","1596":"1596","May 1557":"mai 1557","1470":"1470","1492":"1492","1490":"1490","1549":"1549","Nedging, Suffolk, England, United Kingdom":"Nedging, Suffolk, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Semer, Suffolk, England":"Semer, Suffolk, Angleterre","Brettenham, Suffolk, England":"Brettenham, Suffolk, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Christopher Ungle est né en 1490, à Semer, Suffolk, Angleterre, son père, Xpoferi Ungle, avait 20 ans et sa mère, Elizabeth of Suffolk, avait 25 ans. Il a eu au moins 1 fille avec Agnes Barker. Il est décédé en 1568, dans sa ville natale, à l’âge de 78 ans, et a été enterré à Brettenham, Suffolk, Angleterre."},"de":{"1490–1568":"1490–1568","1492–1557"